Test case 111: The only good permutation is [3,2,1][3,2,1][3,2,1]. We construct CCC as following:

C1=A1+BP1=A1+B3=10−1=9C_1 = A_1 + B_{P_1} = A_1 + B_3 = 10 - 1 = 9C1​=A1​+BP1​​=A1​+B3​=10−1=9;
C2=A2−BP2=A2−B2=5−(−4)=9C_2 = A_2 - B_{P_2} = A_2 - B_2 = 5 - (-4) = 9C2​=A2​−BP2​​=A2​−B2​=5−(−4)=9;
C3=A3−BP3=A3−B1=2−(−7)=9C_3 = A_3 - B_{P_3} = A_3 - B_1 = 2 - (-7) = 9C3​=A3​−BP3​​=A3​−B1​=2−(−7)=9.

Here all elements of array CCC are equal. It can be shown that for all other permutations, it is impossible to create such an array CCC. Thus, the count of good permutations is 111.
Test case 222: The good permutations are [2,1,3],[3,1,2][2,1,3], [3, 1, 2][2,1,3],[3,1,2]. We construct CCC as following using [2,1,3][2, 1, 3][2,1,3]:

C1=A1−BP1=A1−B2=6−5=1C_1 = A_1 - B_{P_1} = A_1 - B_2 = 6 - 5 = 1C1​=A1​−BP1​​=A1​−B2​=6−5=1;
C2=A2+BP2=A2+B1=7+(−6)=1C_2 = A_2 + B_{P_2} = A_2 + B_1 = 7 + (-6) = 1C2​=A2​+BP2​​=A2​+B1​=7+(−6)=1;
C3=A3−BP3=A3−B3=8−7=1C_3 = A_3 - B_{P_3} = A_3 - B_3 = 8 - 7 = 1C3​=A3​−BP3​​=A3​−B3​=8−7=1.

Here all elements of array CCC are equal. It can be shown that for [3,1,2][3, 1, 2][3,1,2], it is possible to create such an array CCC. Thus, the count of good permutations is 222.
